You cannot do that. See [this post][1] for more details.

There is no such thing as an &#39;owner&#39;, so you cannot get the calling instance, unless an explicit reference to the parent is specified:

    class A {
        int b;
        A(int b, int c) {
            this.b = b;
            new D(this, c);
        }
    }

    class D {
        D(A a, int c) {
            ...
        }
    }

It seems that either according to the library your are not supposed to get such instance, or it is poorly designed.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5022604/java-how-does-a-component-know-its-owner

